{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563878"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:06:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:06:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16911"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16911"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.08,0.8,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9601"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"691"},{"type":"tags","id":"1022"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"11137"},{"type":"tags","id":"11139"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22668"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the labour ward at 34 weeks gestation with spontaneous rupture of membranes and regular contractions. This is her first pregnancy which has been otherwise uncomplicated. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a breech presentation. On vaginal examination, she is 6 cm dilated. She proceeds to emergency caesarean section. At surgery, the uterus is noted to have a serosal indentation with two distinct horns partially fused at the isthmus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arcuate uterus","Septate uterus","Bicornuate uterus","Unicornuate uterus","Uterus didelphys"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with preterm labour and breech presentation, which are both more common in women with m\u00fcllerian duct anomalies. The surgical findings of two distinct uterine horns with a serosal indentation is classic of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebicornuate uterus\u003C/strong\u003E, which results from incomplete fusion of the m\u00fcllerian ducts during embryological development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptate uterus\u003C/strong\u003E would show a normal external uterine contour with an internal septum dividing the cavity. This is also a m\u00fcllerian duct anomaly but would not show two distinct horns externally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterus didelphys\u003C/strong\u003E represents complete failure of m\u00fcllerian duct fusion, resulting in two separate uterine cavities, each with its own cervix and often a longitudinal vaginal septum. This is more severe than the findings described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Earcuate uterus\u003C/strong\u003E represents a minor indentation at the fundus of the uterus and would not show two distinct horns. This variant is considered a normal variation rather than a true anomaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnicornuate uterus\u003C/strong\u003E results from the failed development of one m\u00fcllerian duct, resulting in a single-horned uterus, which is not consistent with the findings described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicornuate uterus is associated with adverse pregnancy outcomes including preterm delivery, malpresentation, and increased caesarean section rates. The diagnosis is often made incidentally during caesarean section, though it can be diagnosed on imaging such as 3D ultrasound or MRI if suspected antenatally.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bicornuate uterus is associated with increased risk of preterm labour and breech presentation.","Diagnosis of bicornuate uterus is often made incidentally during caesarean section.","M\u00fcllerian duct anomalies should be considered in patients presenting with malpresentation or preterm labour."],"references":["Akhtar MA, Saravelos SH, Li TC, Jayaprakasan K; on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Reproductive implications and management of congenital uterine anomalies. Scientific Impact Paper No. 62. BJOG. 2019 Nov 20; DOI: 10.1111/1471-0528.15968.","Jayaprakasan K, Ojha K. Diagnosis of Congenital Uterine Abnormalities: Practical Considerations. J Clin Med. 2022 Feb 25;11(5):1251. doi: 10.3390/jcm11051251. PMID: 35268343; PMCID: PMC8911320."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16911"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98470"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:41:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:41:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9601"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":